# jobhound_core Development Guidelines

Spec-driven workflow via `.specify` and `/speckit.*` commands. Update this file when plans change (or run the Specify update script when wired).

## Active Technologies

- Go 1.24 — standard library first; `net/http` / `html` / `encoding/json` for Tier-1 API and static fetchers
- `github.com/PuerkitoBio/goquery` for HTML sources (Tier 2)
- `github.com/go-rod/rod` + session cookies file for LinkedIn (Tier 3)
- PostgreSQL + GORM + migrations — jobs, history, profile, dedup
- Temporal — workflows/activities for manual runs (scheduled auto-refresh is product backlog until specced)
- Claude API for scoring; product delivery channels (e.g. HTTP/API) per specs—third-party push notifications out of MVP scope
- Local: Docker Compose (Postgres + Temporal); production: GCP (see `specs/000-epic-overview`)

## Project Structure

```text
cmd/agent/               # agent binary (composition + long-running agent; not the future public API binary)
cmd/worker/              # Temporal worker: config dial, register each module's workflows
cmd/migrate/             # SQL migrations CLI
cmd/retention/           # retention CLI (when used)
# cmd/api/               # add when product HTTP API exists; thin composition (Group -> NewHTTPHandler)
internal/domain/schema/  # shared kernel types: Job, ScoredJob (import path often aliased e.g. `jobdata` when `package schema` collides)
internal/domain/utils/   # shared kernel: StableJobID, NormalizeListingURL, AssignStableID (alias e.g. `domainutils` inside `package utils`)
internal/config/         # env keys + typed loaders only; feature code must not os.Getenv shared knobs
internal/platform/pgsql/ # GORM Postgres + pool; GormGetter; integration migration tests
internal/collectors/     # Collector contract + sources + schema/ (module data model at collectors root, not under handlers/)
internal/collectors/handlers/debughttp/  # dev-only HTTP handler layout
internal/jobs/           # jobs module: contract, schema/, impl/, storage/, workflows/ as needed
internal/llm/            # contract, providers, mock/, utils/ — no loose helpers at module root
internal/pipeline/       # contract, stage types at root; stage impl in utils/; impl/ if needed
internal/reference/      # optional demos
internal/publicapi/      # product HTTP: handlers/, schema/, utils/ (path/query + JSON Schema validate)
tests/integration/       # optional; `integration` build tag
migrations/              # SQL migration files
```

**Collectors `schema/`**: module-local **data model** — structs, enums, named constants, wire payloads, errors as for any feature module (`internal/collectors/schema/` only — same level as `contract.go`, `handlers/`, `bootstrap/`). Do not nest `schema/` under `handlers/debughttp` or other adapters.

**Debug HTTP today**: `internal/collectors/handlers/debughttp/` is not the product API. Layout: `handler.go` with `NewHTTPHandler(...)` and `registerRoutes()`; one `.go` file per route; shared `helpers.go` / `response.go`. Debug POST request types (and other collector wire/model types) live in `internal/collectors/schema/`. Wire from `cmd/agent` -> `debughttp.NewHTTPHandler(...)`. One-line package comment stating dev-only.

## Module Layout (non-negotiable for feature code)

- **`contract.go`** (module root) — exported interfaces and sentinel errors only. May be split by concern (`api.go`, `errors.go`, `temporal.go`). **No standalone helper functions at the module root** — those go in `utils/`, even if two lines.
- **`impl/`** — application service / use cases only (folder name is `impl`, not `service`). **No Temporal SDK imports** (`go.temporal.io/sdk/...`) inside `impl/` — Temporal-to-domain mapping belongs in `workflows/`.
- **`storage/`** — persistence only; this name only (no `repository/`).
- **`schema/`** — module-local **data model** (not “HTTP DTOs only”): structs, **enums**, **named constants** that belong to the model (status values, keys, caps when they are contract data), request/response bodies, handler/workflow/activity payloads, module-local **exported errors** where they are part of the surface. **Pure functions** stay in **`utils/`** or **`impl/`**. No global schema repo — types stay in the module.
- **`handlers/`** — one file per route, plus `handler.go` (registerRoutes — full route inventory at a glance); `helpers.go` for ALL shared parsing helpers (path values, query params, pagination, stage digits, etc.); `response.go` for all write helpers. **Never define package-level functions inside a route file** — if it is not a method on the handler struct, it goes in `helpers.go` or `response.go`. **Exception: `internal/publicapi/handlers`** — **all** shared HTTP helpers (path/query, JSON read/write, CORS) live in **`internal/publicapi/utils/`**; embeds stay in **`handlers/json_schema/`** + **`schemas_embed.go`**; call **`publicapi/utils.ReadValidatedJSON`** etc. from route files (see Canonical Patterns).
- **`workflows/`** — **required** when the module uses Temporal (not optional). `New...` constructor explicitly calls `RegisterWorkflow` for every workflow. Temporal-to-domain mapping helpers go in `workflows/mappers.go` (or `workflows/utils/`). `activities/` for activity structs and methods.
- **`utils/`** — small helpers for that module only. Standalone functions that would otherwise float at the module root belong here.

Temporal connection lives in `internal/config`; workflow/activity code under `internal/<feature>/workflows/`. Full pattern catalogue: `.specify/memory/constitution.md`.

## Canonical Patterns

### Enum types

Every exported string-based enum type in `schema/` must have all of the following — a bare `Valid() bool` is not sufficient:

- `String() string` — returns the raw string value
- `Equals(str string) bool` — returns `string(e) == str`
- `Pointer() *T` — returns a pointer (for optional fields)
- `FromValue(str string) (T, error)` — parse with a descriptive error listing valid values
- Package-level `ValuesT() []T` — all known values
- Package-level `FromStringT(str string) (T, error)` — delegates to `FromValue`

### HTTP request validation

**`internal/publicapi` (product API):** embed JSON Schema next to routes — `//go:embed json_schema/<name>.schema.json` in the `handlers` package (same workflow as `omg-ap` `pkg/transactions/handlers`: `ValidateRequestBySchema` there, here **`publicapi/utils.ValidateJSONInstance`** + **`publicapi/utils.ReadValidatedJSON`**). Then decode into a typed struct in **`publicapi/schema/`** with `DisallowUnknownFields()`. Do not hand-roll the same rules in handler `if` chains when a schema can express them.

Other feature modules: typed request/response (and other wire) structs in **`schema/`** + `DisallowUnknownFields()`; add embedded JSON Schema when structural validation is non-trivial.

**Forbidden**: `map[string]json.RawMessage` with per-field existence checks (`if _, has := raw["field"]; !has`). Never in handler code.

## Anti-Pattern Reference

| Anti-pattern | Correct approach |
|---|---|
| `map[string]json.RawMessage` + per-field existence checks in handler | Typed struct in `schema/` + `publicapi/utils.ReadJSON` / JSON schema validate |
| Package-level function defined inside a route file (`get_foo.go`, `post_bar.go`) | Move to `helpers.go` or `response.go` (or `internal/publicapi/utils/` for public API: path/query, JSON read/write, CORS) |
| `Valid() bool` as the only method on an enum type | Full canonical enum: `String` / `Equals` / `Pointer` / `FromValue` / `Values` / `FromString` |
| Standalone helper function at module root (e.g. `func DefaultSourceIDs()` in `slots/sources.go`) | Move to `internal/<module>/utils/` |
| Temporal SDK (`go.temporal.io/sdk/...`) imported inside `impl/` | Move to `workflows/mappers.go` or `workflows/utils/` |
| `workflows/` folder absent when module uses Temporal | `workflows/` is required, not optional |
| Describing a pattern as "do it like <project>" | Name the pattern explicitly (e.g. "Canonical Enum", "schema-first JSON validation") |
| Dedicated `*_test.go` for trivial `utils/`, schema-only, or enum-only code | Test **handlers**, **`impl/`**, or **`storage/`**; thin helpers are exercised indirectly |

## Testing

- **Unit**: `*_test.go` next to the code, **same package** as the implementation (idiomatic Go).
- **Scope**: unit tests belong at **boundaries** — a **concrete HTTP handler/route** (mux-level), an **`impl/`** service, or **`storage/`** persistence. **Do not** maintain tests whose only purpose is **`utils/`** helpers, bare **`schema/`** types, or **enum** plumbing (unless behavior is non-trivial). Cover thin helpers **through** handler or service tests.
- **Integration**: `//go:build integration`; run `make test-integration` or `go test -tags=integration ./...` (needs env such as `JOBHOUND_DATABASE_URL` for DB tests, `JOBHOUND_TEMPORAL_ADDRESS` + running worker for Temporal integration tests where applicable).
- Do not rely on `export_test.go` or external `tests/unit/...` trees for ordinary package tests.

## Commands

- `make build` — compile `./cmd/agent` to `bin/agent` and `./cmd/worker` to `bin/worker`
- `make run` — build and run agent
- `make run-worker` — build and run Temporal worker (`JOBHOUND_TEMPORAL_ADDRESS` required)
- `make test` — `go test ./...` (excludes `integration`-tagged tests)
- `make test-integration` — `go test -tags=integration ./...`
- `make fmt` / `make vet` / `make tidy`

## Code Style

- Go 1.24 conventions; interfaces on module boundaries in `internal/<feature>/contract.go` (or split files); persistence only under `internal/<feature>/storage`
- No secrets or real `.env` in git — document `JOBHOUND_*` names in `specs/*/contracts/environment.md`, `README.md`, and `internal/config` (do not duplicate long env lists in the Makefile)
- **Config**: all shared `JOBHOUND_*` (and other app) env names and parsing live in `internal/config`; `cmd/*` loads and passes structs into `internal/*`
- Table-driven tests where behavior branches; keep `main` / `cmd` **thin** — composition only, no business rules
- **Comments**: prefer clear names and structure over comment walls. Do not add large banner comments or redundant docblocks on every method; document **non-obvious** invariants, edge cases, or public API where `godoc` matters. If the code is obvious, leave it uncommented

